{"title_page": "Youth Justice Board", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name = Youth Justice Board\n| native_name         = \n|image = YJB logo Gov.uk.jpg\n|formation = {{start date and age|30 September 1998}}\n|status = [[Non-departmental public body]]\n|headquarters = [[London]]\n|leader_title = CEO \n|leader_name = Colin Allars\n|leader_title2 = Chairman\n|leader_name2 = Charlie Taylor\n|budget =  \n|remarks = \n|region_served = [[England and Wales]]\n|website = {{url|https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Youth Justice Board''' ({{lang-cy|Bwrdd Cyfiawnder Ieuenctid}}), for England and Wales (YJB) is a [[non-departmental public body]] created by the [[Crime and Disorder Act 1998]] to oversee the youth justice system for England and Wales. It is sponsored by the [[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]], and its Board members are appointed by the Secretary of State for Justice. It also receives funding from the Home Office and the [[Department for Education]]. In November 2011 the government dropped plans, contained in the Public Bodies Bill, to abolish the Youth Justice Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Online | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15861943|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Functions==\n\nThe YJB's primary function is to monitor the operation of the youth justice system and the provision of youth justice services. Within England and Wales it is responsible for:\n\n* using information and evidence to form an expert view of how to get the best outcomes for children who offend and for victims of crime\n* advising the Secretary of State for Justice and those working in youth justice services about how well the system is operating, and how improvements can be made\n* identifying and sharing best practice\n* [https://yjresourcehub.uk/yjb-effective-practice/youth-justice-kits/item/364-yjb-launches-young-person-participation-strategy.html promoting the voice of the child]\n* commissioning research and publishing information in connection with good practice\n* monitoring the youth justice system and the provision of youth justice services\n* making grants, with the approval of the Secretary of State, for the purposes of the operation of the youth justice system and services\n* providing information technology related assistance for the operation of the youth justice system and services\n\n==Board Members==\nMembers of the YJB's Board are appointed by the [[Secretary of State for Justice]]. The following people are current YJB Board Members:\n* Charlie Taylor (Chair)\n* Sir [[Alan Thorpe Richard Wood]]\n* Ben Byrne\n* Brian Tytherleigh\n* Dr Gillian Fairfield\n* Keith Fraser\n* [[Keith Towler]]\n* Mairead Healy\n* Professor [[Neal Hazel]]\n* Neil Rhodes\n* Sharon Gray\n\nThe YJB's current Chief Executive is Colin Allars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/colin-allars|title=Youth Justice Board website|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>  The organisation has about 100 staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Youth Justice Board website |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales/about | accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Chairmen of the YJB==\n*September 1998\u2013June 2003 : [[Norman Warner, Baron Warner| Lord Norman Warner]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Lord Warner: I'll tackle 'national disgrace' of Birmingham children's services |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jun/11/norman-warner-tackles-birminghams-childrens-services-michael-gove\n | accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*June 2003\u2013April 2004 : Sir Charles Pollard (Acting)<ref>{{cite web|title=Children and Young People Now |url=https://www.cypnow.co.uk/Other/article/interview-crime-prevention-is-best-sir-charles-pollard-acting-chair-of-the-youth-justice-board| accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*April 2004\u2013January 2007 : [[Rod Morgan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Young at heart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/aug/16/youthjustice.law| accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*February 2007\u2013February 2008 : Graham Robb (Interim)\n*February 2008\u2013March 2014 : [[Frances Done]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Across the divide|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/jul/16/youthjustice| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n*March 2014\u2013February 2017 : [[Tom McNally, Baron McNally| Lord Tom McNally]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord McNally appointed new Chair of Youth Justice Board|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/lord-mcnally-appointed-new-chair-of-youth-justice-board| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n*March 2017\u2013April 2020 : Charlie Taylor<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Taylor|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/charlie-taylor| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales Youth Justice Board]\n* [http://yjbpublications.justice.gov.uk/en-gb/Scripts/default.asp?eP= YJB Publications]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)}}\n\n[[Category:Prison-related organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-departmental public bodies of the United Kingdom government]]\n[[Category:Youth organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name = Youth Justice Board\n| native_name         = \n|image = YJB logo Gov.uk.jpg\n|formation = 1998\n|status = [[Non-departmental public body]]\n|headquarters = [[London]]\n|leader_title = CEO \n|leader_name = Colin Allars\n|leader_title2 = Chairman\n|leader_name2 = Charlie Taylor\n|budget =  \n|remarks = \n|region_served = [[England and Wales]]\n|website = {{url|https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Youth Justice Board''' ({{lang-cy|Bwrdd Cyfiawnder Ieuenctid}}), for England and Wales (YJB) is a [[non-departmental public body]] created by the [[Crime and Disorder Act 1998]] to oversee the youth justice system for England and Wales. It is sponsored by the [[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]], and its Board members are appointed by the Secretary of State for Justice. It also receives funding from the Home Office and the [[Department for Education]]. In November 2011 the government dropped plans, contained in the Public Bodies Bill, to abolish the Youth Justice Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Online | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15861943|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Functions==\n\nThe YJB's primary function is to monitor the operation of the youth justice system and the provision of youth justice services. Within England and Wales it is responsible for:\n\n* using information and evidence to form an expert view of how to get the best outcomes for children who offend and for victims of crime\n* advising the Secretary of State for Justice and those working in youth justice services about how well the system is operating, and how improvements can be made\n* identifying and sharing best practice\n* [https://yjresourcehub.uk/yjb-effective-practice/youth-justice-kits/item/364-yjb-launches-young-person-participation-strategy.html promoting the voice of the child]\n* commissioning research and publishing information in connection with good practice\n* monitoring the youth justice system and the provision of youth justice services\n* making grants, with the approval of the Secretary of State, for the purposes of the operation of the youth justice system and services\n* providing information technology related assistance for the operation of the youth justice system and services\n\n==Board Members==\nMembers of the YJB's Board are appointed by the [[Secretary of State for Justice]]. The following people are current YJB Board Members:\n* Charlie Taylor (Chair)\n* Sir [[Alan Thorpe Richard Wood]]\n* Ben Byrne\n* Brian Tytherleigh\n* Dr Gillian Fairfield\n* Keith Fraser\n* [[Keith Towler]]\n* Mairead Healy\n* Professor [[Neal Hazel]]\n* Neil Rhodes\n* Sharon Gray\n\nThe YJB's current Chief Executive is Colin Allars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/colin-allars|title=Youth Justice Board website|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>  The organisation has about 100 staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Youth Justice Board website |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales/about | accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Chairmen of the YJB==\n*September 1998\u2013June 2003 : [[Norman Warner, Baron Warner| Lord Norman Warner]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Lord Warner: I'll tackle 'national disgrace' of Birmingham children's services |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jun/11/norman-warner-tackles-birminghams-childrens-services-michael-gove\n | accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*June 2003\u2013April 2004 : Sir Charles Pollard (Acting)<ref>{{cite web|title=Children and Young People Now |url=https://www.cypnow.co.uk/Other/article/interview-crime-prevention-is-best-sir-charles-pollard-acting-chair-of-the-youth-justice-board| accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*April 2004\u2013January 2007 : [[Rod Morgan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Young at heart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/aug/16/youthjustice.law| accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*February 2007\u2013February 2008 : Graham Robb (Interim)\n*February 2008\u2013March 2014 : [[Frances Done]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Across the divide|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/jul/16/youthjustice| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n*March 2014\u2013February 2017 : [[Tom McNally, Baron McNally| Lord Tom McNally]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Lord McNally appointed new Chair of Youth Justice Board|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/lord-mcnally-appointed-new-chair-of-youth-justice-board| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n*March 2017\u2013April 2020 : Charlie Taylor<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Taylor|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/charlie-taylor| accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/youth-justice-board-for-england-and-wales Youth Justice Board]\n* [http://yjbpublications.justice.gov.uk/en-gb/Scripts/default.asp?eP= YJB Publications]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)}}\n\n[[Category:Prison-related organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-departmental public bodies of the United Kingdom government]]\n[[Category:Youth organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "4321edit1234", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Youth_Justice_Board"}
{"title_page": "Parimatch (company)", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Parimatch\n| logo =PM Logo NEW.jpg\n| logo_size =\n| industry = [[Betting]]\n| founded = 1994 \n| hq_location_city = [[Limassol]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Cyprus]]\n| key_people = Sergey Portnov (CEO) <ref>https://www.menshealth.com/uk/mental-strength/a30493418/meet-the-ceo-with-tyson-and-mcgregor-on-speed-dial/</ref>\n| products = Bookmaking, betting shops, online gambling\n| num_employees = 2000\n| website = https://parimatch.global\n}}\n'''Parimatch''' is an international sports betting company with headquarters in [[Limassol]], [[Cyprus]],  founded in 1994.<ref>https://www.casinonewsdaily.com/2020/01/21/bf-games-to-roll-out-online-casino-content-with-parimatch/</ref>\n\n==History==\nParimatch was established in 1994 in [[Kyiv]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>https://calvinayre.com/2019/06/04/press-releases/parimatch-enters-partnership-with-fast-track/</ref> The company entered the Russian market in 1998. Online betting website was launched in 2000  and was one the first among bookmakers in the CIS region.<ref>https://sobitie.com.ua/novosti/parimatch-proryv-goda-i-pobeda-srazu-v-dvuh-nominaciyah</ref>\nIn 2004 Parimatch expanded to the Belarusian market.<ref>https://www.top100bookmakers.com/countries/by.php|title=Online Bookmakers in Belarus</ref> In 2005 Parimatch began operations in [[Moldova]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>http://www.betplus.info/obzor-bk-pari-match/</ref>\nIn 2015 Parimatch entered the [[Kazakhstan]] market and began cooperation with Federbet to prevent match fixing.<ref>https://bookmaker-ratings.com.ua/ru/news/pari-match-i-federbet-za-god-vy-yavili-bolee-30-stranny-h-matchej/</ref> In 2017 the company began operations in Tanzania and Cyprus.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/features/2018/05/01/parimatch-ceo-sergey-portnov-wild-decision-tanzania/</ref> In December 2018 Parimatch's CEO, Sergey Portnov won Leader of the year award at the SBC Awards held in London.<ref>https://www.igamingtimes.com/2018/12/05/parimatch-ceo-sbc-awards-online-betting-company/</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 Parimatch signed Conor McGregor as its brand ambassador.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/marketing/2019/02/06/mma-superstar-conor-mcgregor-new-branding-parimatch/</ref>\n<ref>https://themaclife.com/featured-posts/serious-conor-mcgregor-stars-joker-themed-parimatch-commercial/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.rt.com/sport/471671-conor-mcgregor-press-conference-watch/</ref> In July 2019 [[Mike Tyson]] became brand ambassador of Parimatch.<ref>https://www.gamingintelligence.com/marketing/45627-parimatch-names-mike-tyson-as-new-brand-ambassador/</ref> In February 2020 the company joined the Esports Integrity Commission to assist with battling cheating and fraud in esports.<ref>https://esportsinsider.com/2020/02/parimatch-esports-integrity-commission/</ref>\n\n==License==\nParimatch operates under local licenses issued by the regulatory authorities of each country in [[Cyprus]], [[Belarus]], [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Tajikistan]]. Parimatch brand is represented as a franchise with local licenses in [[Russia]],<ref>https://bettingbusiness.ru/articles/0010368-sergej-portnov-po-dohodnosti-biznesa-na-postsovetskom-prostranstve-rossiya-zanimaet-pervoe-mesto</ref> Tanzania,<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/press-releases/2019/09/13/54231/african-superstar-diamond-platnumz-is-a-new-brand-ambassador-for-parimatch-africa/</ref> \nThe company also carries out its activity under the international license of Cura\u00e7ao (eGaming) <ref>https://validator.curacao-egaming.com/validate?domain=www.parimatch.com&seal_id=b1c1be59c55c3af1710c1c520e5bcf494fab047709bae28d1dfec7040fd1d50050647e4cf34e4594b90a48da9d9c7756&stamp=a0df17379c756ee73ea58263e249c42c</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n*Company is an official sponsor of the national both football and basketball teams<ref>https://www.strategya.com/bk-pari-match-stala-sponsorom-chempionata-i-sbornoj-ukrainy-po-basketbolu/</ref> of [[Ukraine]], Ukrainian Hockey League,<ref>https://xsport.ua/hockey_s/news/parimatch-prodolzhil-sotrudnichestvo-s-ukrainskoy-khokkeynoy-ligoy_343505/</ref> Greco-Roman Wrestling Federation of Ukraine <ref>http://borba.com.ua/news/942-generalnim-sponsorom-federacyi-greko-rimskoyi-borotbi-ukrayini-stala-kompanya-parimatch.html,</ref> Ukrainian beach soccer team and Ukrainian Basketball Championship.\n*Premium partner of [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|FC Shakhtar]].<ref>https://shakhtar.com/en/news/2017/july/7_news/7_shakhtar-and-tm-parimatch-are-partners-now</ref><ref>https://ua.tribuna.com/football/1076609114.html</ref>\n*General sponsor of the [[Cyprus]] football club APOEL.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/europe/2019/10/14/parimatch-extends-apoel-fc-sponsorship-deal/</ref><ref>https://bookmaker-ratings.ru/summa-sdelki-bk-pari-match-i-fk-apoe-l-sostavila-okolo-300-ty-s</ref>\n*Official sponsor of the UFC in EMEA region.<ref>http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/ufc-takes-a-bet-with-parimatch-deal</ref>\n*Official sponsor of the esports club Virtus.pro.<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/latest-news/2019/12/26/61212/parimatch-announces-new-partnership-with-virtus-pro/</ref> \n*In July 2018 UFC and Parimatch announced a multi-year partnership that establishes Parimatch as the \u201cOfficial Betting and Wagering Partner of UFC\u201d across the entire EMEA region, excluding the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/latest-news/2018/07/16/23917/parimatch-signs-international-ufc-deal/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sirplay]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://parimatch.global official website]\n\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Parimatch\n| logo =PM Logo NEW.jpg\n| logo_size =\n| industry = [[Betting]]\n| founded = 1994 \n| hq_location_city = [[Limassol]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Cyprus]]\n| key_people = Sergey Portnov (CEO) <ref>https://www.menshealth.com/uk/mental-strength/a30493418/meet-the-ceo-with-tyson-and-mcgregor-on-speed-dial/</ref>\n| products = Bookmaking, betting shops, online gambling\n| num_employees = 2000\n| website = https://parimatch.global\n}}\n'''Parimatch''' is an international sports betting company with headquarters in [[Limassol]], [[Cyprus]],  founded in 1994.<ref>https://www.casinonewsdaily.com/2020/01/21/bf-games-to-roll-out-online-casino-content-with-parimatch/</ref>\n\n==History==\nParimatch was established in 1994 in [[Kyiv]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>https://calvinayre.com/2019/06/04/press-releases/parimatch-enters-partnership-with-fast-track/</ref> The company entered the Russian market in 1998. Online betting website was launched in 2000  and was one the first among bookmakers in the CIS region.<ref>https://sobitie.com.ua/novosti/parimatch-proryv-goda-i-pobeda-srazu-v-dvuh-nominaciyah</ref>\nIn 2004 Parimatch expanded to the Belarusian market.<ref>https://www.top100bookmakers.com/countries/by.php|title=Online Bookmakers in Belarus</ref> In 2005 Parimatch began operations in [[Moldova]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>http://www.betplus.info/obzor-bk-pari-match/</ref>\nIn 2015 Parimatch entered the [[Kazakhstan]] market and began cooperation with Federbet to prevent match fixing.<ref>https://bookmaker-ratings.com.ua/ru/news/pari-match-i-federbet-za-god-vy-yavili-bolee-30-stranny-h-matchej/</ref> In 2017 the company began operations in Tanzania and Cyprus.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/features/2018/05/01/parimatch-ceo-sergey-portnov-wild-decision-tanzania/</ref> In December 2018 Parimatch's CEO, Sergey Portnov won Leader of the year award at the SBC Awards held in London.<ref>https://www.igamingtimes.com/2018/12/05/parimatch-ceo-sbc-awards-online-betting-company/</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 Parimatch signed Conor McGregor as its brand ambassador.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/marketing/2019/02/06/mma-superstar-conor-mcgregor-new-branding-parimatch/</ref>\n<ref>https://themaclife.com/featured-posts/serious-conor-mcgregor-stars-joker-themed-parimatch-commercial/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.rt.com/sport/471671-conor-mcgregor-press-conference-watch/</ref> In July 2019 [[Mike Tyson]] became brand ambassador of Parimatch.<ref>https://www.gamingintelligence.com/marketing/45627-parimatch-names-mike-tyson-as-new-brand-ambassador/</ref> In February 2020 the company joined the Esports Integrity Commission to assist with battling cheating and fraud in esports.<ref>https://esportsinsider.com/2020/02/parimatch-esports-integrity-commission/</ref>\n\n==License==\nParimatch operates under local licenses issued by the regulatory authorities of each country in [[Cyprus]], [[Belarus]], [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Tajikistan]]. Parimatch brand is represented as a franchise with local licenses in [[Russia]],<ref>https://bettingbusiness.ru/articles/0010368-sergej-portnov-po-dohodnosti-biznesa-na-postsovetskom-prostranstve-rossiya-zanimaet-pervoe-mesto</ref> Tanzania,<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/press-releases/2019/09/13/54231/african-superstar-diamond-platnumz-is-a-new-brand-ambassador-for-parimatch-africa/</ref> \nThe company also carries out its activity under the international license of Cura\u00e7ao (eGaming) <ref>https://validator.curacao-egaming.com/validate?domain=www.parimatch.com&seal_id=b1c1be59c55c3af1710c1c520e5bcf494fab047709bae28d1dfec7040fd1d50050647e4cf34e4594b90a48da9d9c7756&stamp=a0df17379c756ee73ea58263e249c42c</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n*Company is an official sponsor of the national both football and basketball teams<ref>https://www.strategya.com/bk-pari-match-stala-sponsorom-chempionata-i-sbornoj-ukrainy-po-basketbolu/</ref> of [[Ukraine]], Ukrainian Hockey League,<ref>https://xsport.ua/hockey_s/news/parimatch-prodolzhil-sotrudnichestvo-s-ukrainskoy-khokkeynoy-ligoy_343505/</ref> Greco-Roman Wrestling Federation of Ukraine <ref>http://borba.com.ua/news/942-generalnim-sponsorom-federacyi-greko-rimskoyi-borotbi-ukrayini-stala-kompanya-parimatch.html,</ref> Ukrainian beach soccer team and Ukrainian Basketball Championship.\n*Premium partner of [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|FC Shakhtar]].<ref>https://shakhtar.com/en/news/2017/july/7_news/7_shakhtar-and-tm-parimatch-are-partners-now</ref><ref>https://ua.tribuna.com/football/1076609114.html</ref>\n*General sponsor of the [[Cyprus]] football club APOEL.<ref>https://sbcnews.co.uk/europe/2019/10/14/parimatch-extends-apoel-fc-sponsorship-deal/</ref><ref>https://bookmaker-ratings.ru/summa-sdelki-bk-pari-match-i-fk-apoe-l-sostavila-okolo-300-ty-s</ref>\n*Official sponsor of the UFC in EMEA region.<ref>http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/ufc-takes-a-bet-with-parimatch-deal</ref>\n*Official sponsor of the esports club Virtus.pro.<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/latest-news/2019/12/26/61212/parimatch-announces-new-partnership-with-virtus-pro/</ref> In July 2018 UFC and Parimatch announced a multi-year partnership that establishes Parimatch as the \u201cOfficial Betting and Wagering Partner of UFC\u201d across the entire EMEA region, excluding the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>https://europeangaming.eu/portal/latest-news/2018/07/16/23917/parimatch-signs-international-ufc-deal/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sirplay]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://parimatch.global official website]\n\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "TTalex w", "label": "safe", "comment": "Formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parimatch_(company)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montana", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Montana, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montana\n| map1            = COVID-19 cases in Montana by county.svg\n| places          = \n| legend1         = Counties with positive cases in Montana as of March 23: {{legend|#BB2919|Confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Montana]], U.S.\n| first_case      = Broadwater, Gallatin, Silver Bow, and Yellowstone Counties\n| arrival_date    = March 13, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 108\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.mt.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Montana]] on March 13, 2020.<ref name=\":5\" /> As of March 27, 2020, the Montana Department of Public Health and Human Services (MDPHHS) has confirmed 108 positive cases in the state.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://dphhs.mt.gov/publichealth/cdepi/diseases/coronavirusmt|title=Coronavirus|website=dphhs.mt.gov|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Montana medical cases chart}}\n\n=== March ===\n\n==== March 11 ====\nOn March 11, the Governor of [[Maryland]], [[Larry Hogan]], announced that a part-time Montana and part-time Maryland resident tested positive for coronavirus in [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland]]. The woman in her 70s is a part-time resident of [[Lake County, Montana|Lake County]], and because this was her primary residence, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] announced that she would be considered Montana's first case. The woman, however, had not been in Montana since November 2019 and did not come into contact with anyone in Montana. Her being counted as a Montana case is still not officially confirmed, however, as the MDPHHS does not report the case in their official totals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvq.com/maryland-governors-office-montana-woman-diagnosed-with-covid-19|title=Montanan diagnosed with coronavirus in Maryland did not have disease in Montana|date=2020-03-11|website=KTVQ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 12 ====\nOn March 12, Governor [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] declared a state of emergency in Montana. Although no cases were confirmed in the state at the time, the emergency declaration helped prepare state and local governments for the future impact the disease would have on Montana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mt.gov/governor-bullock-declares-state-of-emergency-in-montana-related-to-covid-19|title=GOVERNOR BULLOCK DECLARES STATE OF EMERGENCY IN MONTANA RELATED TO COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=montana.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== March 13 ====\nOn March 13, Governor Bullock announced the first four cases of coronavirus that were within the state of Montana. The patients included a [[Gallatin County, Montana|Gallatin County]] man in his 40s who traveled internationally, a [[Yellowstone County, Montana|Yellowstone County]] woman in her 50s who traveled internationally, a [[Silver Bow County, Montana|Silver Bow County]] man in his 50s who traveled to [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and a [[Broadwater County, Montana|Broadwater County]] man in his 50s who also traveled to Washington.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/helena-news/governor-bullock-confirms-four-presumptively-positive-coronavirus-cases-in-montana|title=Governor Bullock confirms four presumptively positive Coronavirus cases in Montana|date=2020-03-14|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/covid-19-in-montana-new-cases-two-public-leaders-in-isolation|title=COVID-19 in Montana: new cases, two public leaders in isolation|date=2020-03-15|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 14 ====\nLate on March 14, the governor's office announced the confirmation of two more positive cases, both of which are from [[Missoula County, Montana|Missoula County]]: a woman in her 30s who was identified as the Montana Commissioner of Higher Education and a man in his 50s. The commissioner and the man from Silver Bow County who was confirmed on March 13 were both present at a Board of Regents meeting in [[Dillon, Montana|Dillon]] on March 5, where it is believed they both became exposed.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== March 15 ====\nMid-day March 15, Governor Bullock issued an executive order that closed all public schools in the state for two weeks beginning March 16 and lasting until March 27. In addition, the governor ordered the suspension of all nursing home visits with the exception of end-of-life situations. Governor Bullock also suggested, but did not ban, the gathering of all groups over 50 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.krtv.com/news/montana-and-regional-news/bullock-directs-two-week-closure-of-public-k-12-schools-in-montana|title=Bullock directs two-week closure of public K-12 schools in Montana|date=2020-03-15|website=KRTV|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Lewis and Clark Library announced that they would close beginning on March 17 until further notice. All overdues were ended and the due date of all books were extended to May 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/local-news/helena-news/coronavirus-closure-lewis-clark-library-will-close-beginning-tuesday-mar-17|title=Coronavirus Closure: Lewis & Clark Library will close beginning Tuesday Mar. 17|date=2020-03-15|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 16 ====\nThe city of [[Helena, Montana|Helena]] was placed under a 10-day-long state of emergency by Mayor [[Wilmot Collins]] on the afternoon of March 16.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/city-of-helena-declares-state-of-emergency|title=City of Helena declares State of Emergency|date=2020-03-16|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Bullock announced on the evening of March 16 that two new positive cases had been confirmed in Montana: a Missoula County man and a Yellowstone County woman, both of whom are in their 20s. This announcement increased the total number of cases to 8.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/covid-19-cases-in-montana-rise-to-9|title=Two more COVID-19 cases in Montana|date=2020-03-17|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17 ====\n[[Austin Vetter|Bishop Austin Vetter]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Helena]] announced on March 17 that all public Masses and related gatherings in the diocese would be banned until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/helena-roman-catholic-diocese-suspends-public-masses-and-other-events|title=Helena Roman Catholic Diocese suspends public masses and other events|date=2020-03-18|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on March 17, Governor Bullock announced an additional case in the state. He also announced that small businesses would be able to apply for Small Business Administration (SBA) loans and uninsured Montanans would have the cost of their coronavirus tests covered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/governor-bullock-to-announce-several-new-efforts-to-respond-to-covid-19-cases-and-its-impact-on-montanans|title=Governor Bullock to announce new efforts to respond to COVID-19 cases and its impact on Montanans|date=2020-03-17|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 18 ====\nLate March 18, Governor Bullock's office announced two more positive cases in Montana, which increased the cases to 12 in the state. The patients were a Missoula County man in his 50s and a Gallatin County man in his 60s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/governor-bullock-confirms-two-more-positive-cases-of-coronavirus-in-montana|title=Governor Bullock confirms two more positive cases of Coronavirus in Montana|date=2020-03-19|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 20 ====\nOn March 20, Governor Bullock announced measures that would close all sit-down and dine-in food services, all alcoholic beverage businesses, casinos, and other businesses that serve groups of people at one time. The closure began at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. that same day and last until midnight on March 28.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvq.com/news/coronavirus/bullock-shuts-down-restaurant-and-other-business-statewide|title=Bullock shuts down dine-in restaurants and other businesses statewide|date=2020-03-20|website=KTVQ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21 ====\nBy March 21, the Montana Department of Public Health confirmed an additional 6 cases, bringing the total to 27 cases of coronavirus in the state of Montana. Three additional cases were confirmed in [[Cascade County, Montana|Cascade County]] on the evening of March 21, bringing the total number of cases to at least 30.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/3-cases-of-coronavirus-covid-19-confirmed-in-cascade-county|title=3 cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) confirmed in Cascade County|date=2020-03-22|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n[[Helena, Montana|Helena]] Mayor [[Wilmot Collins]] placed the city under a state of local disaster emergency on March 16. Lasting 10 days, the emergency declaration activated the response and recovery units of all city disaster plans. This also allowed for the possibility to declare a curfew or quarantine, though city officials said that none had been decided at that time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nGovernor Bullock announced major closures in establishments that seat many people, including restaurants, alcohol beverage businesses, cigar bars, gyms and health clubs, movie theaters, nightclubs, bowling alleys, and casinos on March 20. Restaurants are allowed, under the order, to use delivery, walk-or-drive-up, or drive-thru services. Alcoholic beverage delivery was also allowed. The limitations began that same day at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. and would expire at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 27.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nGovernor Bullock signed a pair of executive orders on March 26 enforcing a stay-at-home order for all Montana residents beginning at midnight on March 28 and ending on April 10. The executive order also forced all non-essential businesses to fully close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.mt.gov/Portals/223/Documents/Stay%20at%20Home%20Directive.pdf?ver=2020-03-26-173332-177|title=Stay at Home Directive|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=Office of the Governor, State of Montana|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Montana<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\nUpdated March 27, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Broadwater County, Montana|Broadwater]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cascade County, Montana|Cascade]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Flathead County, Montana|Flathead]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Gallatin County, Montana|Gallatin]]\n|39\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hill County, Montana|Hill]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Jefferson County, Montana|Jefferson]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lewis and Clark County, Montana|Lewis and Clark]]\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lincoln County, Montana|Lincoln]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Madison County, Montana|Madison]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Meagher County, Montana|Meagher]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Missoula County, Montana|Missoula]]\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Park County, Montana|Park]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ravalli County, Montana|Ravalli]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Roosevelt County, Montana|Roosevelt]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Silver Bow County, Montana|Silver Bow]]\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Toole County, Montana|Toole]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Yellowstone County, Montana|Yellowstone]]\n|20\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |108\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://covid19.mt.gov/ Information] from the State of Montana\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Montana]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Montana]]\n[[Category:Health in Montana]]\n[[Category:2020 in Montana|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montana\n| map1            = COVID-19 cases in Montana by county.svg\n| places          = \n| legend1         = Counties with positive cases in Montana as of March 23: {{legend|#BB2919|Confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS