nd the man from Silver Bow County who was confirmed on March 13 were both present at a Board of Regents meeting in [[Dillon, Montana|Dillon]] on March 5, where it is believed they both became exposed.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== March 15 ====\nMid-day March 15, Governor Bullock issued an executive order that closed all public schools in the state for two weeks beginning March 16 and lasting until March 27. In addition, the governor ordered the suspension of all nursing home visits with the exception of end-of-life situations. Governor Bullock also suggested, but did not ban, the gathering of all groups over 50 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.krtv.com/news/montana-and-regional-news/bullock-directs-two-week-closure-of-public-k-12-schools-in-montana|title=Bullock directs two-week closure of public K-12 schools in Montana|date=2020-03-15|website=KRTV|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Lewis and Clark Library announced that they would close beginning on March 17 until further notice. All overdues were ended and the due date of all books were extended to May 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/local-news/helena-news/coronavirus-closure-lewis-clark-library-will-close-beginning-tuesday-mar-17|title=Coronavirus Closure: Lewis & Clark Library will close beginning Tuesday Mar. 17|date=2020-03-15|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 16 ====\nThe city of [[Helena, Montana|Helena]] was placed under a 10-day-long state of emergency by Mayor [[Wilmot Collins]] on the afternoon of March 16.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/city-of-helena-declares-state-of-emergency|title=City of Helena declares State of Emergency|date=2020-03-16|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Bullock announced on the evening of March 16 that two new positive cases had been confirmed in Montana: a Missoula County man and a Yellowstone County woman, both of whom are in their 20s. This announcement increased the total number of cases to 8.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/covid-19-cases-in-montana-rise-to-9|title=Two more COVID-19 cases in Montana|date=2020-03-17|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17 ====\n[[Austin Vetter|Bishop Austin Vetter]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Helena]] announced on March 17 that all public Masses and related gatherings in the diocese would be banned until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/helena-roman-catholic-diocese-suspends-public-masses-and-other-events|title=Helena Roman Catholic Diocese suspends public masses and other events|date=2020-03-18|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on March 17, Governor Bullock announced an additional case in the state. He also announced that small businesses would be able to apply for Small Business Administration (SBA) loans and uninsured Montanans would have the cost of their coronavirus tests covered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/governor-bullock-to-announce-several-new-efforts-to-respond-to-covid-19-cases-and-its-impact-on-montanans|title=Governor Bullock to announce new efforts to respond to COVID-19 cases and its impact on Montanans|date=2020-03-17|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 18 ====\nLate March 18, Governor Bullock's office announced two more positive cases in Montana, which increased the cases to 12 in the state. The patients were a Missoula County man in his 50s and a Gallatin County man in his 60s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/governor-bullock-confirms-two-more-positive-cases-of-coronavirus-in-montana|title=Governor Bullock confirms two more positive cases of Coronavirus in Montana|date=2020-03-19|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 20 ====\nOn March 20, Governor Bullock announced measures that would close all sit-down and dine-in food services, all alcoholic beverage businesses, casinos, and other businesses that serve groups of people at one time. The closure began at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. that same day and last until midnight on March 28.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvq.com/news/coronavirus/bullock-shuts-down-restaurant-and-other-business-statewide|title=Bullock shuts down dine-in restaurants and other businesses statewide|date=2020-03-20|website=KTVQ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21 ====\nBy March 21, the Montana Department of Public Health confirmed an additional 6 cases, bringing the total to 27 cases of coronavirus in the state of Montana. Three additional cases were confirmed in [[Cascade County, Montana|Cascade County]] on the evening of March 21, bringing the total number of cases to at least 30.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kxlh.com/news/coronavirus/3-cases-of-coronavirus-covid-19-confirmed-in-cascade-county|title=3 cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) confirmed in Cascade County|date=2020-03-22|website=KXLH|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n[[Helena, Montana|Helena]] Mayor [[Wilmot Collins]] placed the city under a state of local disaster emergency on March 16. Lasting 10 days, the emergency declaration activated the response and recovery units of all city disaster plans. This also allowed for the possibility to declare a curfew or quarantine, though city officials said that none had been decided at that time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nGovernor Bullock announced major closures in establishments that seat many people, including restaurants, alcohol beverage businesses, cigar bars, gyms and health clubs, movie theaters, nightclubs, bowling alleys, and casinos on March 20. Restaurants are allowed, under the order, to use delivery, walk-or-drive-up, or drive-thru services. Alcoholic beverage delivery was also allowed. The limitations began that same day at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. and would expire at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 27.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nGovernor Bullock signed a pair of executive orders on March 26 enforcing a stay-at-home order for all Montana residents beginning at midnight on March 28 and ending on April 10. The executive order also forced all non-essential businesses to fully close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.mt.gov/Portals/223/Documents/Stay%20at%20Home%20Directive.pdf?ver=2020-03-26-173332-177|title=Stay at Home Directive|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=Office of the Governor, State of Montana|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Montana<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\nUpdated March 27, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Broadwater County, Montana|Broadwater]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cascade County, Montana|Cascade]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Flathead County, Montana|Flathead]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Gallatin County, Montana|Gallatin]]\n|39\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hill County, Montana|Hill]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Jefferson County, Montana|Jefferson]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lewis and Clark County, Montana|Lewis and Clark]]\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lincoln County, Montana|Lincoln]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Madison County, Montana|Madison]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Meagher County, Montana|Meagher]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Missoula County, Montana|Missoula]]\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Park County, Montana|Park]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ravalli County, Montana|Ravalli]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Roosevelt County, Montana|Roosevelt]]\n|1\n|-\n| sty