{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name =2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width =\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease =[[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date = March 07, 2020\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases = 133\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases = 9 (hospitalized) \n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 3\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the epicenters of COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of 6 COVID-19 cases. The town has [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine. Just over 1 in 1,000 residents there have tested positive for COVID-19, with more testing underway.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases reached 11 there, raising the towns infection rate to approximately 1 per 732 residents.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Alaska-cases-map (9).png|thumb|Up-to-date map of confirmed COVID-19 cases in Alaska]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref>{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated March 23, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Region{{efn| Economic regions are for measurement purposes and do not have their own governance structures.}}\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]/<br>[[Southcentral Alaska]]\n|65\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Gulf Coast\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Interior Alaska|Interior]]\n|35\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Matanuska-Susitna Valley|Mat-Su]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Alaska North Slope|Northern]]\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Southeast Alaska|Southeast]]\n|22\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Southwest Alaska|Southwest]]\n|0\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |133\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/default.aspx Coronavirus information] from [[Alaska Department of Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alaska]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alaska|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Health in Alaska]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name =2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width =\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease =[[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date = March 07, 2020\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases = 133\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases = 9 (hospitalized) \n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 3\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the epicenters of COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\n{{Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of 6 COVID-19 cases. The town has [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine. Just over 1 in 1,000 residents there have tested positive for COVID-19, with more testing underway.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases reached 11 there, raising the towns infection rate to approximately 1 per 732 residents.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n[[File:Alaska-cases-map (9).png|thumb|Up-to-date map of confirmed COVID-19 cases in Alaska]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref>{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated March 23, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Region{{efn| Economic regions are for measurement purposes and do not have their own governance structures.}}\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]/<br>[[Southcentral Alaska]]\n|65\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Gulf Coast\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Interior Alaska|Interior]]\n|35\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Matanuska-Susitna Valley|Mat-Su]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Alaska North Slope|Northern]]\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Southeast Alaska|Southeast]]\n|22\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Southwest Alaska|Southwest]]\n|0\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |133\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/default.aspx Coronavirus information] from [[Alaska Department of Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alaska]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alaska|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Health in Alaska]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "add short description per WP:SHORT DESC", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "National personal autonomy", "text_new": "The [[Austromarxism|Austromarxist]] principle of '''national personal autonomy''' (\"personal principle\"), developed by [[Otto Bauer]] in his 1907 book ''Die Nationalit\u00e4tenfrage und die Sozialdemokratie'' (The Nationalities Question and Social Democracy) was seen by him a way of gathering the geographically divided members of the same nation to \"organize nations not in territorial bodies but in simple association of persons\", thus radically disjoining the nation from the [[territory (country subdivision)|territory]] and making of the nation a non-territorial [[Voluntary association|association]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bauer|first=Otto|others=Joseph O'Donnell (Translator)|title=The question of nationalities and social democracy|editor=Ephraim J. Nimni|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|year=2000|pages=696|isbn=978-0-8166-3265-7}}</ref> The other ideological founders of the concept were another Austromarxist, [[Karl Renner]], in his 1899 essay ''Staat und Nation'' (State and Nation),<ref>All of Renner's essay is reproduced in an English translation in{{cite book|title=National cultural autonomy and its contemporary critics|editor=Ephraim Nimni|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|pages=260|isbn=978-0-415-24964-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP_9TccTwnYC}}</ref> and the [[Bundism|Jewish Labour Bundist]] [[Vladimir Medem]], in his 1904 essay ''Di sotsial-demokratie un di natsionale frage'' (Social Democracy and the National Question).<ref>{{lang-yi|Medem, V.}} 1943. \u201cDi sotsial-demokratie un di natsionale frage\u201d (1904). Vladimir Medem: Tsum tsvantsikstn yortsayt. New York: New York: Der Amerikaner Reprezentants fun Algemeynem Yidishn Arbeter-Bund (\u2018Bund\u2019) in Poyln, pp. 173-219.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gechtman|first=Roni|date=December 2008|title=National-Cultural Autonomy and 'Neutralism': Vladimir Medem's Marxist Analysis of the National Question, 1903-1920|journal=[[Socialist Studies (1983)|Socialist Studies]]|volume=III|issue=1|issn=1918-2821 |url=http://journals.sfu.ca/sss/index.php/sss/article/view/23|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Medem==\nIn his 1904 text, Medem exposed his version of the concept:\n<blockquote>\n\"Let us consider the case of a country composed of several national groups, e.g. Poles, Lithuanians and Jews. Each national group would create a separate movement. All citizens belonging to a given national group would join a special organisation that would hold cultural assemblies in each region and a general cultural assembly for the whole country. The assemblies would be given financial powers of their own: either each national group would be entitled to raise taxes on its members, or the state would allocate a proportion of its overall budget to each of them. Every citizen of the state would belong to one of the national groups, but the question of which national movement to join would be a matter of personal choice and no authority would have any control over his decision. The national movements would be subject to the general legislation of the state, but in their own areas of responsibility they would be autonomous and none of them would have the right to interfere in the affairs of the others\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Plassereaud|first=Yves|date=May 2000|title=Choose Your Own Nationality  or The Forgotten History of Cultural Autonomy|journal=[[Le Monde diplomatique]]|language=English|url=http://www.panarchy.org/plasseraud/choice.html}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Supporters==\nThis principle was later adopted by various parties, among them the [[Jewish Socialist Workers Party]] from its foundation in 1906, the [[General Jewish Labour Bund in Lithuania, Poland and Russia|Jewish Labour Bund]] at its August 1912 Conference (when the motion \"On National Cultural Autonomy\" became part of the Bund's program), the [[Dashnak|Armenian social democrats]], the Russian [[Constitutional Democratic Party]] (''Kadets'') at its June 1917's Ninth Congress,<ref name=bowring>Bill Bowring, \"Burial and resurrection, Karl Renner's controversial influence on the \"national question\" in Russia\", in{{cite book|title=National cultural autonomy and its contemporary critics|editor=Ephraim Nimni|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|pages=260|isbn=978-0-415-24964-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP_9TccTwnYC}}</ref> the first Ottoman then Greek [[Socialist Workers' Federation]] of [[Thessaloniki]], the left-wing [[Zionist]]s ([[Hashomer Hatzair]]) in favour of a [[one-state solution|binational solution]] in [[History of Palestine|Palestine]], the Jewish [[Folkspartei]] (inspired by [[Simon Dubnov]], who had developed a concept of Jewish autonomy close to Bauer's), and the [[Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania]] (DAHR) after 1989.\n\n==Opponents==\nThe whole concept was strongly opposed by the [[Bolshevik]]s. [[Stalin]]'s pamphlet ''[[Marxism and the National Question]]'' (1913) was their ideological reference on the matter, along with [[Lenin]]'s ''Critical Remarks on the National Question'' (December 1913), in particular in the chapter \"Cultural-National Autonomy\".<ref name=bowring/><ref name=\"Stalin\">{{cite book|last=Stalin|first=Joseph|title=Marxism and the National Question|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|date=Prosveshcheniye, Nos. 3-5, March\u2013May 1913|url=http://www.marx.org/reference/archive/stalin/works/1913/03.htm|accessdate=2009-11-12|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"lenin\">{{cite book|last=Lenin|first=Vladimir|title=Critical Remarks on the National Question|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|date=Prosveshcheniye Nos. 10, 11 and 12, October\u2013December 1913|url=http://www.marx.org/archive/lenin/works//1913/crnq/index.htm|accessdate=2009-11-12|language=English}}</ref> (Stalin was later People's Commissar of Nationalities from 1917 - 1923.) Lenin's and Stalin's critiques of the national personal autonomy concept were later joined by the Catalan [[Andreu Nin]] in his article ''The Austrian School, National Emancipation Movements'' (1935).<ref name=\"nin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/nin/1935/xx/austromarx.htm|title=Austro-Marxism and the National Question (chapter in National Emancipation Movements)|last=Nin|first=Andr\u00e9s|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|year=1935|language=English|accessdate=2009-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\nIt was adopted as an official policy in the short-lived [[Ukrainian People's Republic]] (1917\u20131920) and in the interwar [[History of Estonia (1920-1939)|Estonian Republic]] (1925  Law on Personal Autonomy), and it was included in the Declaration Concerning the Protection of Minorities in Lithuania by the [[League of Nations]] in 1925.<ref name=\"bowring\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.einst.ee/factsheets/cult_auton/|title=Law on Cultural Autonomy for National Minorities|year=1925|publisher=The [[Estonian Institute]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forost.ungarisches-institut.de/pdf/19220512-1.pdf|title=Declaration concerning the protection of minorities in Lithuania|year=1922|publisher=[[League of Nations]]|accessdate=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n\nThe autonomous representative structure of the [[Yishuv|Palestinian Jews]] between 1920 and 1949, the [[Assembly of Representatives (Mandate Palestine)|Asefat ha-Nivharim]], can also be considered as an implementation of the national personal autonomy principle.\n\nSince the fall of the [[Soviet Union]] and its satellites regimes, the national personal autonomy is the principle on which legislation applying to ethnic minorities has been enacted {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} such as [[Estonia]]'s (1993 National Minorities Cultural Autonomy Act),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaltext.ee/text/en/XX00038.htm|title=National Minorities Cultural Autonomy Act|year=1993|publisher=The [[Estonian Ministry of Justice]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Hungary]]'s Act LXXVII of 1993 on the Rights of National and Ethnic Minorities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3ae6b4e90.html |title=Act LXXVII of 1993 on the Rights of National and Ethnic Minorities|year=1993|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Latvia]]'s 1991 Law on Unrestricted Development and Right to Cultural Autonomy of Latvia's Nationalities and Ethnic Groups,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3ae6b4e90.html|title=Law on Unrestricted Development and Right to Cultural Autonomy of Latvia's Nationalities and Ethnic Groups (last amended 1994)|year=1991|publisher=[[UNHCR]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Lithuania]]'s 1989 Law on Ethnic Minorities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minelres.lv/NationalLegislation/Lithuania/Lithuania_Minorities_English.htm\n|title=Law on ethnic minorities|year=1989|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Russia]]'s 1996 Law on National-Cultural Autonomies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecmi.de/download/report_30.pdf\n|title=National-Cultural Autonomies and Inter-Ethnic Relations in the Kaliningrad Oblast|last=J\u00e4rve|first=Priit|date=July 2002|publisher=[[European Centre for Minority Issues]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> and [[Ukraine]]'s 1992 Law on National Minorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minelres.lv/NationalLegislation/Ukraine/Ukraine_Minorities_English.htm|title=Law on National Minorities|year=1992|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Millet (Ottoman Empire)]]\n*[[Jewish Autonomism]] - [[Kehilla (modern)|Kehilla]] - [[Assembly of Representatives (Mandate Palestine)|Asefat ha-Nivharim]]\n*[[Language policy#Based on non-territorialized individual rights|Non-territorial language policy]]\n*[[Consociationalism]]\n*[[Plurinationalism]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Marxism]]\n[[Category:Minority rights]]\n[[Category:Bundism]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Autonomy]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Austromarxism|Austromarxist]] principle of '''national personal autonomy''' (\"personal principle\"), developed by [[Otto Bauer]] in his 1907 book ''Die Nationalit\u00e4tenfrage und die Sozialdemokratie'' (The Nationalities Question and Social Democracy) was seen by him a way of gathering the geographically divided members of the same nation to \"organize nations not in territorial bodies but in simple association of persons\", thus radically disjoining the nation from the [[territory (country subdivision)|territory]] and making of the nation a non-territorial [[Voluntary association|association]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bauer|first=Otto|others=Joseph O'Donnell (Translator)|title=The question of nationalities and social democracy|editor=Ephraim J. Nimni|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|year=2000|pages=696|isbn=978-0-8166-3265-7}}</ref> The other ideological founders of the concept were another Austromarxist, [[Karl Renner]], in his 1899 essay ''Staat und Nation'' (State and Nation),<ref>All of Renner's essay is reproduced in an English translation in{{cite book|title=National cultural autonomy and its contemporary critics|editor=Ephraim Nimni|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|pages=260|isbn=978-0-415-24964-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP_9TccTwnYC}}</ref> and the [[Bundism|Jewish Labour Bundist]] [[Vladimir Medem]], in his 1904 essay ''Di sotsial-demokratie un di natsionale frage'' (Social Democracy and the National Question).<ref>{{lang-yi|Medem, V.}} 1943. \u201cDi sotsial-demokratie un di natsionale frage\u201d (1904). Vladimir Medem: Tsum tsvantsikstn yortsayt. New York: New York: Der Amerikaner Reprezentants fun Algemeynem Yidishn Arbeter-Bund (\u2018Bund\u2019) in Poyln, pp. 173-219.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gechtman|first=Roni|date=December 2008|title=National-Cultural Autonomy and 'Neutralism': Vladimir Medem's Marxist Analysis of the National Question, 1903-1920|journal=[[Socialist Studies (1983)|Socialist Studies]]|volume=III|issue=1|issn=1918-2821 |url=http://journals.sfu.ca/sss/index.php/sss/article/view/23|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Medem==\nIn his 1904 text, Medem exposed his version of the concept:\n<blockquote>\n\"Let us consider the case of a country composed of several national groups, e.g. Poles, Lithuanians and Jews. Each national group would create a separate movement. All citizens belonging to a given national group would join a special organisation that would hold cultural assemblies in each region and a general cultural assembly for the whole country. The assemblies would be given financial powers of their own: either each national group would be entitled to raise taxes on its members, or the state would allocate a proportion of its overall budget to each of them. Every citizen of the state would belong to one of the national groups, but the question of which national movement to join would be a matter of personal choice and no authority would have any control over his decision. The national movements would be subject to the general legislation of the state, but in their own areas of responsibility they would be autonomous and none of them would have the right to interfere in the affairs of the others\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Plassereaud|first=Yves|date=May 2000|title=Choose Your Own Nationality  or The Forgotten History of Cultural Autonomy|journal=[[Le Monde diplomatique]]|language=English|url=http://www.panarchy.org/plasseraud/choice.html}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Supporters==\nThis principle was later adopted by various parties, among them the [[Jewish Socialist Workers Party]] from its foundation in 1906, the [[General Jewish Labour Bund in Lithuania, Poland and Russia|Jewish Labour Bund]] at its August 1912 Conference (when the motion \"On National Cultural Autonomy\" became part of the Bund's program), the [[Dashnak|Armenian social democrats]], the Russian [[Constitutional Democratic Party]] (''Kadets'') at its June 1917's Ninth Congress,<ref name=bowring>Bill Bowring, \"Burial and resurrection, Karl Renner's controversial influence on the \"national question\" in Russia\", in{{cite book|title=National cultural autonomy and its contemporary critics|editor=Ephraim Nimni|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|pages=260|isbn=978-0-415-24964-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zP_9TccTwnYC}}</ref> the first Ottoman then Greek [[Socialist Workers' Federation]] of [[Thessaloniki]], the left-wing [[Zionist]]s ([[Hashomer Hatzair]]) in favour of a [[one-state solution|binational solution]] in [[History of Palestine|Palestine]], the Jewish [[Folkspartei]] (inspired by [[Simon Dubnov]], who had developed a concept of Jewish autonomy close to Bauer's), and the [[Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania]] (DAHR) after 1989.\n\n==Opponents==\nThe whole concept was strongly opposed by the [[Bolshevik]]s. [[Stalin]]'s pamphlet ''[[Marxism and the National Question]]'' (1913) was their ideological reference on the matter, along with [[Lenin]]'s ''Critical Remarks on the National Question'' (December 1913), in particular in the chapter \"Cultural-National Autonomy\".<ref name=bowring/><ref name=\"Stalin\">{{cite book|last=Stalin|first=Joseph|title=Marxism and the National Question|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|date=Prosveshcheniye, Nos. 3-5, March\u2013May 1913|url=http://www.marx.org/reference/archive/stalin/works/1913/03.htm|accessdate=2009-11-12|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"lenin\">{{cite book|last=Lenin|first=Vladimir|title=Critical Remarks on the National Question|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|date=Prosveshcheniye Nos. 10, 11 and 12, October\u2013December 1913|url=http://www.marx.org/archive/lenin/works//1913/crnq/index.htm|accessdate=2009-11-12|language=English}}</ref> (Stalin was later People's Commissar of Nationalities from 1917 - 1923.) Lenin's and Stalin's critics of the national personal autonomy concept were later joined by the Catalan [[Andreu Nin]] in his article ''The Austrian School, National Emancipation Movements'' (1935).<ref name=\"nin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/nin/1935/xx/austromarx.htm|title=Austro-Marxism and the National Question (chapter in National Emancipation Movements)|last=Nin|first=Andr\u00e9s|publisher=[[Marxists Internet Archive]]|year=1935|language=English|accessdate=2009-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\nIt was adopted as an official policy in the short-lived [[Ukrainian People's Republic]] (1917\u20131920) and in the interwar [[History of Estonia (1920-1939)|Estonian Republic]] (1925  Law on Personal Autonomy), and it was included in the Declaration Concerning the Protection of Minorities in Lithuania by the [[League of Nations]] in 1925.<ref name=\"bowring\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.einst.ee/factsheets/cult_auton/|title=Law on Cultural Autonomy for National Minorities|year=1925|publisher=The [[Estonian Institute]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forost.ungarisches-institut.de/pdf/19220512-1.pdf|title=Declaration concerning the protection of minorities in Lithuania|year=1922|publisher=[[League of Nations]]|accessdate=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n\nThe autonomous representative structure of the [[Yishuv|Palestinian Jews]] between 1920 and 1949, the [[Assembly of Representatives (Mandate Palestine)|Asefat ha-Nivharim]], can also be considered as an implementation of the national personal autonomy principle.\n\nSince the fall of the [[Soviet Union]] and its satellites regimes, the national personal autonomy is the principle on which legislation applying to ethnic minorities has been enacted {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} such as [[Estonia]]'s (1993 National Minorities Cultural Autonomy Act),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaltext.ee/text/en/XX00038.htm|title=National Minorities Cultural Autonomy Act|year=1993|publisher=The [[Estonian Ministry of Justice]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Hungary]]'s Act LXXVII of 1993 on the Rights of National and Ethnic Minorities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3ae6b4e90.html |title=Act LXXVII of 1993 on the Rights of National and Ethnic Minorities|year=1993|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Latvia]]'s 1991 Law on Unrestricted Development and Right to Cultural Autonomy of Latvia's Nationalities and Ethnic Groups,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3ae6b4e90.html|title=Law on Unrestricted Development and Right to Cultural Autonomy of Latvia's Nationalities and Ethnic Groups (last amended 1994)|year=1991|publisher=[[UNHCR]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Lithuania]]'s 1989 Law on Ethnic Minorities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minelres.lv/NationalLegislation/Lithuania/Lithuania_Minorities_English.htm\n|title=Law on ethnic minorities|year=1989|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> [[Russia]]'s 1996 Law on National-Cultural Autonomies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecmi.de/download/report_30.pdf\n|title=National-Cultural Autonomies and Inter-Ethnic Relations in the Kaliningrad Oblast|last=J\u00e4rve|first=Priit|date=July 2002|publisher=[[European Centre for Minority Issues]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref> and [[Ukraine]]'s 1992 Law on National Minorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minelres.lv/NationalLegislation/Ukraine/Ukraine_Minorities_English.htm|title=Law on National Minorities|year=1992|publisher=[[Minority Electronic Resources]]|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Millet (Ottoman Empire)]]\n*[[Jewish Autonomism]] - [[Kehilla (modern)|Kehilla]] - [[Assembly of Representatives (Mandate Palestine)|Asefat ha-Nivharim]]\n*[[Language policy#Based on non-territorialized individual rights|Non-territorial language policy]]\n*[[Consociationalism]]\n*[[Plurinationalism]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Marxism]]\n[[Category:Minority rights]]\n[[Category:Bundism]]\n[[Category:Political science terminology]]\n[[Category:Autonomy]]\n", "name_user": "Asmaybe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOpponents:spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_personal_autonomy"}
{"title_page": "South Carolina Highway 7", "text_new": "{{Other uses|SC 7 (disambiguation){{!}}SC 7}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=7\n|map=SC 7 map.svg\n|length_mi=5.92\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=SCDOTGIS>{{Cite GIS |name=Statewide Highways 2012 |url_download=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/STATEWIDE_HIGHWAYS_2012.zip |publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]] |year=2012 |url_doc=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx}}</ref>\n|established=1956\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=SC|I|526}} in Charleston\n*{{Jct|state=SC|I|26}} in [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|52|US|78}} in North Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=6\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=8\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 7''' ('''SC&nbsp;7''') is a {{convert|5.92|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[state highway (US)|state highway]] in the east-central part of the [[U.S. state]] of [[South Carolina]]. The route connects the [[West Ashley]] part of the city of [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] with [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC&nbsp;7 begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Route 17]] (US&nbsp;17; Savannah Highway) in West Ashley. Here, it also has an [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] with [[Interstate 526]] (I-526). It heads east-northeast to an intersection with [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC&nbsp;61]]. A little while later, it meets the northern terminus of [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC&nbsp;171]]. Then, the highway crosses over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. On the east side of the river, SC&nbsp;7 enters North Charleston. Almost immediately is an interchange with [[Interstate 26 in South Carolina|I-26]]. About {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later, it meets its northern terminus, an intersection with [[U.S. Route 52 in South Carolina|US&nbsp;52]]/[[U.S. Route 78 in South Carolina|US&nbsp;78]] (Rivers Avenue).<ref name=GM>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/32.7903886,-80.0340073/32.8554966,-79.9768423/@32.8230065,-80.0404478,13z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m9!4m8!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-79.989554!2d32.8288856!3s0x88fe7b6c656ba295:0xe0741b65cbc564af!1m0!3e0 |accessdate=February 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|state=SC|county=Charleston|length_ref=<ref name=SCDOTGIS/>}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=4\n|mile=0.00\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|US|17|city1=Charleston|city2=Jacksonboro}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=0.11\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|I|526|dir1=east|city1=North Charleston}}\n|notes=I-526 exit 10; no access to eastbound I-526 from northbound SC&nbsp;7\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=1.29\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|SC|61|name1=Ashley River Road|city1=Folly Beach|city2=Summerville}}\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=3.08\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=south|city1=Johns Island|name1=Old Towne Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of SC&nbsp;171\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=North Charleston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=4.99\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|I|26|city1=Summerville|city2=Charleston}}\n|notes=I-26 exits 216 A\u2013B\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=5.92\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|US|52|US|78|name2=Rivers Avenue|road=Cosgrove Avenue north|city1=Hanahan|city2=Charleston}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; Cosgrove Avenue continues past.\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|United States}}\n* {{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.vahighways.com/scannex/route-log/sc007.htm SC 7 - South Carolina Hwy Index]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|007]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Transportation in North Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|SC 7 (disambiguation){{!}}SC 7}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=SC\n|type=SC\n|route=7\n|map=SC 7 map.svg\n|length_mi=5.92\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=SCDOTGIS>{{Cite GIS |name=Statewide Highways 2012 |url_download=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/pdfs/GIS/STATEWIDE_HIGHWAYS_2012.zip |publisher=[[South Carolina Department of Transportation]] |year=2012 |url_doc=http://dbw.scdot.org/GISMapping/default.aspx}}</ref>\n|established=1956\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=SC|US|17}} in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=SC|I|526}} in Charleston\n*{{Jct|state=SC|I|26}} in [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=SC|US|52|US|78}} in North Charleston\n|counties=[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]]\n|previous_type=SC\n|previous_route=6\n|next_type=SC\n|next_route=8\n}}\n\n'''South Carolina Highway 7''' ('''SC&nbsp;7''') is a {{convert|5.92|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[state highway (US)|state highway]] in the east-central part of the [[U.S. state]] of [[South Carolina]]. The route connects the [[West Ashley]] part of the city of [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] with [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]].\n\n==Route description==\nSC&nbsp;7 begins at an [[Intersection (road)|intersection]] with [[U.S. Route 17 in South Carolina|U.S. Route 17]] (US&nbsp;17; Savannah Highway) in West Ashley. Here, it also has an [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] with [[Interstate 526]] (I-526). It heads east-northeast to an intersection with [[South Carolina Highway 61|SC&nbsp;61]]. A little while later, it meets the northern terminus of [[South Carolina Highway 171|SC&nbsp;171]]. Then, the highway crosses over the [[Ashley River (South Carolina)|Ashley River]]. On the east side of the river, SC&nbsp;7 enters North Charleston. Almost immediately is an interchange with [[Interstate 26 in South Carolina|I-26]]. About {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later, it meets its northern terminus, an intersection with [[U.S. Route 52 in South Carolina|US&nbsp;52]]/[[U.S. Route 78 in South Carolina|US&nbsp;78]] (Rivers Avenue).<ref name=GM>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/32.7903886,-80.0340073/32.8554966,-79.9768423/@32.8230065,-80.0404478,13z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m9!4m8!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-79.989554!2d32.8288856!3s0x88fe7b6c656ba295:0xe0741b65cbc564af!1m0!3e0 |accessdate=February 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|state=SC|county=Charleston|length_ref=<ref name=SCDOTGIS/>}}\n{{SCint\n|location=Charleston\n|lspan=4\n|mile=0.00\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|US|17|city1=Charleston|city2=Jacksonboro}}\n}}\n{{SCint\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=0.11\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|I|526|dir1=East|city1=North Charleston}}\n|notes=Exit 10 (I-526); no access to eastbound I-526 from northbound SC 7\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=1.29\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|SC|61|name1=Ashley River Road|city1=Folly Beach|city2=Summerville}}\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=3.08\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|SC|171|dir1=South|city1=Johns Island|name1=Old Towne Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of SC 171\n}}\n{{SCint\n|location=North Charleston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=4.99\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|I|26|city1=Summerville|city2=Charleston}}\n|notes=Exits 216 A\u2013B (I-26)\n}}\n{{SCint\n|mile=5.92\n|road={{Jct|state=SC|US|52|US|78|city1=Hanahan|city2=Charleston|name2=Rivers Avenue|road=Cosgrove Avenue}}\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=incomplete}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|United States}}\n* {{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.vahighways.com/scannex/route-log/sc007.htm SC 7 - South Carolina Hwy Index]\n\n[[Category:State highways in South Carolina|007]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Transportation in North C